<table border=0 cellpadding=20 cellspacing=0 width=95%>
  <tr> 
    <td><font color="050056" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Abashi on Linkdeath</b></font> 
      <div><font color="#660000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><b>Official_EverQuest_Forums 
        [ 10:45 AM EDT ] -</b></font><font color="ff0000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"> 
        <a href="mailto:ogamok@stratics.com?subject=EQNews">Ogamok</a></font> 
        <div><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"> I found this <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/009053.html"Target="_blank">here</a> on the <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/cgi-bin/Ultimate.cgi?action=intro&BypassCookie=true"Target="_blank">Official Everquest Forums</a><br><br><blockquote><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#050056">There is a problem that has been been brought up here in that past, quite a few times, but has always been dismissed as too difficult, or not worth the effort to fix.<br><br>I am talking about how linkdeaths, accidental and losses of connectivity to the game servers, plague so many of the players of this game. <br><br>Accidental linkdeath is no one's fault, really. It happens to me often, even on a cable modem. Some classes are not terribly bothered by it, other than the frustation of having to log back in, but other classes are terribly wronged by a design feature of the game that punishes certain players whose connections are not as good as others. <br><br>When a player goes linkdead, or logs out, any summoned items or pets the player has disappear. I remember playing as a Magician, summoning my best pet, getting all my food and water, starting out on my adventure, and going linkdead. I'd log back in, and literally have to spend another 15 minutes summoning my things. 15 minutes lost to something that I am sure was never a "balance" issue in the game. (How can you punish a player if his connection is not as stable as another player's?)<br><br><font color="#a00000">I appreciate the time that you took to write this up. Let me see if I can explain the current technology is as much detail.<br><br>Pets can only exist in the world when their owner also exists in the world, meaning that once the owner disappears, so does the pet. At the same time, the character goes linkdead, that character cannot reenter the game until they are removed from the world.<br><br>Once a character is removed from the world, the world has no knowledge of the existence of the character. As such, the world no longer processes data relative to the characater, since the character does not exist. That is why NORENT objects are removed as the character is being removed, since the world has no knowledge of the character once they are gone.<br><br>Certain parts of the description above are core system mechanics for EverQuest that it wouldn't make sense to change after several years of getting them operating just right. That said, we do have some plans to improve the current situation in the works. I can't comment specifically on them until we have some new things implemented and tested on the Test Server.<br><br>-Gordon</font></font></blockquote> </font> 
          <div align="right"><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="http://eq.stratics.com/graphics/tikb.gif" width=5 height=5>&nbsp;<a href="#top">top</a></font></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    <hr width="50%" align="center">
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
