    <td><font color="050056" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Aradune On the Clipping Plane</b></font> 
      <div><font color="#660000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><b>Official_EverQuest_Forums 
        [ 5:24 PM EDT ] -</b></font><font color="ff0000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"> 
        <a href="mailto:ogamok@stratics.com?subject=EQNews">Ogamok</a></font> 
        <div><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"> I found this <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/006032-3.html"target="_blank">here</a> on the <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/cgi-bin/Ultimate.cgi?action=intro&BypassCookie=true"target="_blank">Official Everquest Forums</a><br><br>First a little background on the problem:<br><br><blockquote><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#a00000">What Brad promised is that he understood what the claim was and that we'd look into it.  At no point have we agreed that there is a problem. The screenshots that were posted only show that the when the rain turns off, the fog moves out past the max clipping plane for an instant, then back in. This isn't indicative of there being any problem with the way that the plane works. Many zones have clips that are determined by the area. For instance, Toxxulia Forrest has a max clipping plane that is pretty close because we wanted the zone to appear eerie. <br><br>We're still looking into the issue, but it's not the highest of priorities at this time. The most likely "fix" will be for us to make it so that the plane doesn't extend beyond max when the rain turns off. The net result of this fix is basically nothing, which is why it's not a high priority at the moment. We have already confirmed that the min/max clipping plane boundaries are indeed set to the appropriate limits.<br><br>-Gordon</font></blockquote><br><br>Then Aradune followed up with:<br><br><blockquote><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#a00000">Here's the deal:<br><br>The bug with the rain is very low priority.<br><br>Slightly higher priority is having a game designer to through ALL outdoor zones and revisit the max clipping distance associated with the zone. <br><br>IF the zone doesn't have an artifically limited clip for effect (eg. Toxxulia Forest), the game designer will make the max clip the farthest it can be based on the max distance used when exporting the zone (it can't go farther, else things will cease to draw correctly).<br><br>As stated before, several months ago when I posted on the subject, this is low priority (getting FA style quests in the game, revamping lesser used dungeons, working on Velious, etc. are all higher priority).<br><br>Other than the wierd rain bug and the fact that apparently several zones could indeed have their max clip increased, I do NOT believe there is any 'bug'.<br><br>-Brad </font></blockquote><br><br>And lastly he said:<br><br><blockquote><Font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#a00000">We DID, in my opinion, get to the bottom of it: for some reason, either in code or in data, many of the zones' max clipping planes were apparently reduced at some point.<br><br>I think your problem is with the priority we are assigning this issue, and I apologize that it's not high enough for some of you.<br><br>The plan is to have a game designer go into the data for each zone and move the clipping plane maximum out as appropriate.<br><br>If that fails, we'll look at it in code (which would involve a programmer). But my inclination is that the data change will solve the problem.<br><br>Again, it's not very high on the priority list. The FA style quests are (and are near being ready for testing, btw.), as are the dungeon revamps (which will be focussed on after the FA style quests).<br><br>-Brad</font></blockquote> </font> 
          <div align="right"><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="http://eq.stratics.com/graphics/tikb.gif" width=5 height=5>&nbsp;<a href="#top">top</a></font></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    <hr width="50%" align="center">
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
