    <td><font color="050056" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>New Petition Idea</b></font> 
      <div><font color="#660000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><b>Official_EverQuest_Forums 
        [ 11:35 AM EDT ] -</b></font><font color="ff0000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"> 
        <a href="mailto:ogamok@stratics.com?subject=EQNews">Ogamok</a></font> 
        <div><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"> I found this <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008803.html"Target="_blank">here</a> on the <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/cgi-bin/Ultimate.cgi?action=intro&BypassCookie=true"target="_blank">Official Everquest Forums</a><br><br><blockquote><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#050056">I believe a large part of the perceived customer service problem is that, well, the process is pretty opaque. You /petition, and don't know how many guides/GMs are on (because they're anon) and don't know how many are in front of you in the queue. You ask a GM in chat, and don't know when he'll be able to answer, or even if he saw you. Etc.<br><br>Me: /petition I fell under the world and died when zoning into Qeynos Hills, and want my corpse and EXP back.<br><br>Server: Your petition is number 99 out of 101; there are currently 2 GMs and 8 guides online; we estimate your petition to be answered in 45-70 minutes.<br><br>... 10 minutes later ...<br><br>Me: /petition<br><br>Server: Your petition is number 49 out of 200; there are currently 1 GM and 2 guides online; we estimate your petition to be answered in 80-120 minutes.<br><br>The information is easy to calculate for the server based on the current petition queue and average petition response rate for GMs and guides; add a little slop to the estimate and you have a good time range to print.<br><br>Well, I would like it.<br><br><font color="#a00000">Interesting idea. I don't see any issues that would prevent us from putting something like this in. I'll chat with the team about it and see what they think. And for future reference, can we speak of "increasing customer satisfaction" rather than "reducing customer dis-satisfaction" in the future?<br><br>-Gordon</font></font></blockquote><br><br>Talk about this <a href="http://boards.stratics.com/cgi-bin/boards/eq/showflat.pl?Cat=7,8,9,10,11&Board=eqwestwood&Number=376858&page=0&view=collapsed&sb=5"target="_blank">here</a> </font> 
