    <td><font color="050056" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Discussion of the Week: Fun</b></font> 
      <div><font color="#660000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><b>Official_EverQuest_Forums 
        [ 9:16 AM EDT ] -</b></font><font color="ff0000" size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"> 
        <a href="mailto:ogamok@stratics.com?subject=EQNews">Ogamok</a></font> 
        <div><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"> I found this <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum2/HTML/008866.html"Target="_blank">here</a> on the <a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/cgi-bin/Ultimate.cgi?action=intro&BypassCookie=true"Target="_blank">Official Everquest Forums</a><br><br><blockquote><font face="Verdana" size=2 color="#a00000">Let&#8217;s talk about &#8220;fun&#8221;.<br><br>Last week I queried everyone&#8217;s thoughts regarding a &#8220;Discussion of the Week&#8221;.  Though the number of different responses was almost as great as the number of posts, many of them dealt with fun, or with concepts related to fun.<br><br>I think that it can generally be agreed that EQ&#8217;s customer base is very diverse, and with that diversity comes many different types of players. EQ strives to provide as many different avenues for &#8220;fun&#8221; as possible, leaving it up to the player to make decisions regarding what avenues they wish to pursue. Some find the social aspect of the game to be the most fun, while others have a good time by advancing in levels.<br><br>Some measure it in items, while others prefer character development along the lines of mastering trade skills or languages. Still others want to personally witness as much as possible within game.<br><br>Our goal with EverQuest is to entertain you for the greatest amount of time possible, and to do this we must provide activities that the players consider &#8220;fun&#8221; in nature.  I&#8217;ve spoken many times about the concepts of risk and reward, but those concepts can be broken down to the perception of fun. Setting pure socialization aside, as it is one way of having &#8220;fun&#8221; that does not require a challenge, the goal is that &#8220;rewards&#8221; provide excitement, entertainment, etc. (cf. Fun), to the players that overcome challenges. <br><br>Last week we discussed camping, how it impacts the game, and what the driving forces behind it are. I think that from the responses to that thread, we can agree that camping relates to the concept of &#8220;fun&#8221; in one way or another. Players either enjoy camping itself, or enjoy something that camping will provide, if not the process itself. The social gamer might enjoy camping because of the opportunities for socialization provided in the downtime between kills. The leveling gamer might enjoy the prospect of raising in level. The item gamer looks forward to the items. More indirectly, perhaps the exploring gamer doesn&#8217;t enjoy camping for experience or loot, but gets fun out of exploring new situations, for which they need the levels and items to do, without explicitly caring for those levels or items.<br><br>The questions I&#8217;d like to pose are:<br><br>What is it about EverQuest that entertains you? If you had to label yourself as a particular type of gamer, what would that type be? Though I&#8217;m sure that everyone has particular issues that they feel could use improvement, everyone either has fun in game, or foresees the prospect of having fun sometime in the future. For instance, there are players that feel that once they reach their particular goal (whether it is one of items or levels), they *then* can go have fun.<br><br>If you are of the type that does not feel they are having fun now, and foresees fun once reaching a specific goal, what is that goal? What is it about that goal that makes you feel you can only have fun once you reach it? Internally, we refer to it as a &#8220;comfort-level&#8221;. What defines that comfort-level to you? What do you foresee will be &#8220;fun&#8221; once you&#8217;ve reached that comfort-level?<br><br>When Kunark came out, we raised the level cap. If you define yourself as one who must achieve a comfort level prior to having &#8220;fun&#8221;, did the raising of the level limit also &#8220;raise the bar&#8221; of your comfort level, effectively putting you far below it? Or did you enjoy the level-cap increase? I ask because before the level cap was raised there were thousands of people who were out having &#8220;fun&#8221; in game. Once the cap was raised, the focus for these people quickly shifted back to the &#8220;must-level-fast&#8221; philosophy.<br><br>Assuming that you have &#8220;fun&#8221; outside the tangible effects of levels and items, do you feel that &#8220;fun&#8221; is a just and suitable reward for a risk? Do you have fun outside of the scope of items and levels? Will you give some examples of where you&#8217;ve had fun without a tangible reward? While I understand that players who value only items and levels typically do not have fun outside of the acquisition of those rewards, I would imagine that most fall somewhere in between one player-type an another rather than directly in the middle of one of the ones I&#8217;ve defined. <br><br>If you could make any change to the game, feasible or otherwise, to increase the amount of entertainment you get or fun you have in the game given your particular gaming style, what would that change be? Other thoughts? I&#8217;m looking forward to seeing discussions between the players on their various perceptions of fun. <br><br>This should make for a pretty good discussion. Often here on the boards, we fail to get a good impression of the different types of gamers out there. It&#8217;s not unusual to see two posts on the opposite side of an issue related to &#8220;fun&#8221; claim to both represent the majority. I really doubt there is a &#8220;majority&#8221; for most issues in EverQuest, because as in life, very few things are black and white. <br><br>This is an opportunity to jump in and be heard. <br><br>-Gordon</font></blockquote><br><br>Talk about this <a href="http://boards.stratics.com/cgi-bin/boards/eq/showflat.pl?Cat=7,8,9,10,11&Board=eqwestwood&Number=376734&page=0&view=collapsed&sb=5"target="_blank">here</a> </font> 
          <div align="right"><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="http://eq.stratics.com/graphics/tikb.gif" width=5 height=5>&nbsp;<a href="#top">top</a></font></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    <hr width="50%" align="center">
    </td>
  </tr>
